initial_answer:
[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Software engineering is the discipline that focuses on using computers and computing as tools to design and implement solutions to problems, rather than studying the computers or programming languages themselves.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Software engineering takes the latter view, as shown in Figure 1.3. Instead of investigating hardware design or proving theorems about how algorithms work, a software engineer focuses on the computer as a problem-solving tool.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "It fits into computer science by applying the theories and computer functions studied in computer science, along with understanding the customer's problem, to develop tools and techniques to solve those problems.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "We can view computing in a similar light. We can concentrate on the computers and programming languages, or we can view them as tools to be used in designing and implementing a solution to a problem. Software engineering takes the latter view, as shown in Figure 1.3.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "img",
                "content": null,
                "img_id": "img0_se_theory_practice.pdf__chunk_144_144_44"
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "While computer science focuses on data, data transformation, algorithms, and theoretical aspects, software engineering is more general and applied, focusing on building software products and covering all activities from initial idea to final product.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "At its core, computer science focuses on data, data transformation, and algorithms; advanced courses present designs and programming techniques for specific application domains. In contrast, software engineering focuses on building software products. It looks at all the activities involved in developing a software system from initial idea to final product.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Technical quality focuses on the products and processes, measured with mathematical expressions involving faults, failures, and timing, emphasizing the technical value of software products.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "When the focus of quality assessment is on products and processes, we usually measure quality with mathematical expressions involving faults, failures, and timing. Rarely is the scope broadened to include a business perspective, where quality is viewed in terms of the products and services being provided by the business in which the software is embedded.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Business quality, on the other hand, views quality in terms of the products and services provided by the business in which the software is embedded, focusing on the business value rather than just technical quality.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "quality is viewed in terms of the products and services being provided by the business in which the software is embedded.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Technical quality is important because it ensures the software functions correctly and efficiently, but it does not automatically translate into business value.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "we make decisions based only on the resulting products' technical quality. In other words, we assume that improving technical quality will automatically translate into business value.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Business quality is important because it aligns software development with the business goals and value, ensuring that projects are launched only when there is clear expected business value, such as measurable outcomes like the number of claims processed.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "If there is not clear (expected) business value (expressed quantitatively: number of claims processed, etc.) then we can't launch a systems project. We take very seriously the 'purposeful' requirement phase of the project, when we ask:'why do we want this system?' and 'why do we care?'",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Thus, while technical quality ensures the software's operational performance and reliability, business quality ensures that the software delivers meaningful value to the business, making both perspectives essential for successful software projects.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The issue of business versus technical value is near and dear to our heart . . . and one [on] which we focus a great deal of attention.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Failures in software occur when the software does not meet the requirements specified, such as responding incorrectly to user inputs or unauthorized access.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "What do we mean when we say that our software has failed? Usually,we mean that the software does not do what the requirements describe.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Examples of failures include a system responding to an unauthorized user, which indicates a failure in access control.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "For example, the specification may state that the system must respond to a particular query only when the user is authorized to see the data. If the program responds to an unauthorized user, we say that the system has failed.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Such failures affect the quality of the software product by making it unreliable and not meeting customer expectations, which can lead to loss of trust and additional costs to fix the issues.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Some faults are merely annoying; others cost a great deal of time and money. Still others are lifethreatening.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "Examples of software failures include:",
        "citations": [],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "The IRS automated tax processing system failure, which caused delays in tax refunds and resulted in significant financial costs.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In the early 1980s, the United States Internal Revenue Service (IRS) hired Sperry Corporation to build an automated federal income tax form processing system... the IRS was forced to pay $40.2 million in interest and $22.3 million in overtime wages for its employees who were trying to catch up.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Failures in aviation software where pilot errors and automation issues contributed to accidents, highlighting the critical need for reliable software in safety-critical systems.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Pilots must understand they can't let automation take over responsibility for flying the airplane.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Failures in software can be caused by faults and errors originating from various stages of the software development process.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Thus, the failure is the result of one or more faults in some aspect of the system.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "The faults and errors that cause failures can include:",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The failure may be the result of any of several reasons:",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Incorrect or missing requirements in the specification, such as unspecified categories of authorization.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The specification may be wrong or have a missing requirement. The specification may not state exactly what the customer wants or needs.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Requirements that are impossible to implement given the hardware and software constraints.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The specification may contain a requirement that is impossible to implement, given the prescribed hardware and software.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Faults in system design, such as database and query-language designs that prevent proper authorization.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The system design may contain a fault. Perhaps the database and query-language designs make it impossible to authorize users.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Faults in program design, such as incorrect access control algorithms.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The program design may contain a fault. The component descriptions may contain an access control algorithm that does not handle this case correctly.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Errors in program code, such as improper or incomplete implementation of algorithms.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The program code may be wrong. It may implement the algorithm improperly or incompletely.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Older issues of software magazines such as IEEE Computer and IEEE Software from the 1970s and 1980s often focused on fundamental software engineering challenges, including software faults, failures, and maintenance problems.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "You can find out about software faults and failures by looking in the Risks Forum, moderated by Peter Neumann.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "There are few up-to-date textbooks on software maintenance; most information is best sought in journals and conference proceedings.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "For example, the January 1990 issue of IEEE Software had maintenance, reverse engineering, and design recovery as its theme, while the January 1993 issue addressed special maintenance problems of object-oriented systems.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "IEEE Software 's January 1990 issue had maintenance, reverse engineering, and design recovery as its theme; the January 1993 issue has a good article by Wilde, Matthews, and Huitt on the special maintenance problems of object-oriented systems.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In contrast, more recent issues of software magazines tend to focus on advanced topics such as software quality, testing, usability, and software engineering best practices.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The January 1996 issue of IEEE Software is devoted to software quality.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "There have been several special issues of IEEE Software focused on the topics covered in this chapter. The June 1992 and May 1995 issues looked at reliability, the March 1991 issue focused on testing, and the May 2007 issue addressed test-driven development.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "Recent issues highlight several best practices and technologies:",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "reviews and inspections",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The January/February 2000 issue of IEEE Software contains an editorial by McConnell about software engineering's best influences: reviews and inspections",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "information hiding",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The January/February 2000 issue of IEEE Software contains an editorial by McConnell about software engineering's best influences: information hiding",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
