]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The process to get ready for class or work in the morning can be described as a sequence of states and transitions between those states, similar to a state transition diagram.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Transition diagrams supplement the process model by showing how the states are related to one another.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "For example, the process of starting a car is modeled using Lai's notation, which shows various states such as 'off', 'in pocket', 'drive', and transitions triggered by actions like 'elec_on', 'open_door', and 'drive'.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Lai's notation is a good example of how multiple structures and strategies can be used to capture a great deal of information about the software development process. But it is also useful in organizing and depicting process information about user requirements, as the car example demonstrates.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "[FIGURE 2.11 The process of starting a car (Lai 1991).]",
                "img_id": "img0_se_theory_practice.pdf__chunk_640_642_164"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Similarly, you can model your morning routine by identifying key states such as 'asleep', 'awake', 'getting dressed', 'eating breakfast', and 'ready to leave', and then define transitions between these states triggered by actions or events.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Here is a simple example of a state transition diagram for a morning routine:",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "States in the morning routine",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Asleep",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Awake",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Getting dressed",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Eating breakfast",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Ready to leave",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Transitions between these states could be triggered by actions such as waking up, finishing dressing, finishing breakfast, and so on.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A diagram similar to Figure 2.12 can be drawn to illustrate these states and transitions.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "[FIGURE 2.12 Transition diagram for a car (Lai 1991).]",
                "img_id": "img0_se_theory_practice.pdf__chunk_644_644_165"
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "One software development life-cycle model is the Waterfall model. The main activities performed in this model are requirements analysis, system design, program design, coding, unit and integration testing, system testing, acceptance testing, and operation and maintenance.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "One of the first models to be proposed is the waterfall model , illustrated in Figure 2.1, where the stages are depicted as cascading from one to another (Royce 1970). As the figure  implies, one  development  stage  should  be  completed  before  the  next  begins. Thus, when  all  of  the  requirements  are  elicited  from  the  customer, analyzed  for completeness and consistency, and documented in a requirements document, then the development team can go on to system design activities.The waterfall model presents a very high-level view of what goes on during development, and it suggests to developers the sequence of events they should expect to encounter.",
                "img_id": "img0_se_theory_practice.pdf__chunk_521_524_130"
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "The input to the requirements analysis activity is a statement of desired functions and features expressed by the user, and the output is a set of requirements.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "For example, the requirements analysis and definitions stage need as initial input a statement of desired functions and features that the user expresses in some way. The final output from this stage is a set of requirements",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "Each subsequent activity takes the output of the previous stage as input and produces outputs that feed into the next stage.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "when  all  of  the  requirements  are  elicited  from  the  customer, analyzed  for completeness and consistency, and documented in a requirements document, then the development team can go on to system design activities.",
                "img_id": "img0_se_theory_practice.pdf__chunk_521_524_130"
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "The Waterfall model is well-suited for projects where requirements are well understood and unlikely to change, such as in government or large enterprise systems with fixed specifications.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "It is inappropriate for projects where requirements are expected to evolve or are not well understood at the start, because the model is rigid and does not easily accommodate changes.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Another model is the V model, which extends the waterfall model by emphasizing verification and validation activities corresponding to each development stage.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The V model.",
                "img_id": "img0_se_theory_practice.pdf__chunk_543_543_138"
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "The main activities in the V model include requirements analysis, system design, program design, coding, unit and integration testing, system testing, acceptance testing, and operation and maintenance, with testing activities linked to corresponding development stages.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The V model.",
                "img_id": "img0_se_theory_practice.pdf__chunk_543_543_138"
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "Inputs and outputs are similar to the waterfall model, but the V model explicitly connects testing phases to their corresponding development activities to ensure validation and verification.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Validate requirements",
                "img_id": "img0_se_theory_practice.pdf__chunk_543_543_138"
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Verify design",
                "img_id": "img0_se_theory_practice.pdf__chunk_543_543_138"
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "The V model is well-suited for projects requiring rigorous testing and validation, such as safety-critical systems.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "It is inappropriate for projects with rapidly changing requirements or where iterative development is preferred.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The context also mentions other models like the spiral model and prototyping models, which address learning, risk, and iterative development, but detailed descriptions are not provided in the given context.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In this chapter, we present an overview of different types of process and life-cycle models, including the waterfall model, the V-model, the spiral model, and various prototyping models.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Static modeling depicts the process by showing that inputs are transformed into outputs.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A static model depicts the process, showing that the inputs are transformed to outputs.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Dynamic modeling enacts the process, allowing the user to see how intermediate and final products are transformed over time.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A dynamic model enacts the process, so the user can see how intermediate and final products are transformed over time.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Static modeling is useful for representing the overall transformation of inputs to outputs in a process.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A static model depicts the process, showing that the inputs are transformed to outputs.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Dynamic modeling is useful because it enables simulation of the process, allowing observation of resource flow through activities and the effects of changes before resources are actually expended.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A desirable property of a process model is the ability to enact the process, so that we can watch what happens to resources and artifacts as activities occur. In other words, we want to describe a model of the process and then watch as software shows us how resources flow through activities to become outputs.This dynamic process view enables us to simulate the process and make changes before the resources are actually expended.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "For example, dynamic models can help decide how many testers are needed or when testing should start to finish on schedule, and can evaluate the impact of adding or excluding activities on effort and schedule.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "For example, we can use a dynamic process model to help us decide how many testers we need or when we must initiate testing in order to finish on schedule. Similarly, we can include or exclude activities to see their effects on effort and schedule.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Curtis, Kellner, and Over (1992) identified five desirable properties of process modeling tools and techniques: facilitating human understanding and communication, supporting process improvement, supporting process management, providing automated guidance in performing the process, and supporting automated process execution.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Curtis, Kellner, and Over (1992) have identified five categories of desirable properties: - Facilitates human understanding and communication... - Supports process improvement... - Supports process management... - Provides automated guidance in performing the process... - Supports automated process execution.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Evaluating a process modeling tool such as a tool that checks code components for size and structure against predefined limits demonstrates these properties.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "For example, a tool can check a set of code components, evaluating their size and structure. If size or structure exceeds predefined limits, the developers can be notified before testing begins, and some components may be reviewed and perhaps redesigned.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "This tool can be evaluated against the five desirable properties as follows:",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Facilitates human understanding and communication by providing clear feedback on code components that developers can understand and act upon.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The technique should be able to represent the process in a form that most customers and developers can understand, encouraging communication about the process and agreement on its form and improvements.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Supports process improvement by identifying components that exceed limits, allowing review and redesign before further testing.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The technique should identify the essential components of a development or maintenance process... estimate the impact of changes before the process is actually put into practice.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Supports process management by enabling developers and customers to reason about software attributes such as size and structure, aiding planning and monitoring.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
