        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The process of getting a degree (bachelor's, master's, or PhD) can be described as a work breakdown structure by identifying the major phases, steps, and activities involved in the process.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "analyzing a software development or maintenance project and identifying the phases, steps, and activities, both we and our customers have a better grasp of what is involved in building and maintaining a system.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "For example, the work breakdown structure for getting a degree might include phases such as course enrollment, coursework completion, research or thesis work, and final examination or defense.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "We can describe each activity with four parameters: the precursor, duration, due date, and endpoint.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "An activity graph can be drawn where nodes represent milestones such as completing coursework, submitting thesis proposal, completing research, and defending thesis, and edges represent activities such as attending classes, conducting research, writing thesis, and preparing for defense.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "we can draw an activity graph to depict the dependencies; the nodes of the graph are the project milestones, and the lines linking the nodes represent the activities involved.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The critical path in this activity graph is the longest sequence of dependent activities that determines the minimum time to complete the degree, such as completing all required coursework, research, thesis writing, and defense without delay.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "For each activity, list its precursors and compute the earliest start time, the latest start time, and the slack.Then, identify the critical path.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The organizational structure of a work environment can be classified based on the degree of certainty, stability, uniformity, and repetition in the project.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A National Science Foundation (1983) investigation found that projects with a high degree  of  certainty, stability, uniformity, and  repetition  can  be  accomplished  more effectively  by  a  hierarchical  organizational  structure  such  as  the  chief  programmer team.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Highly structured organizations are suitable for large projects with high certainty and repetition, emphasizing rules, specialization, formality, and a clear hierarchy.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "These projects require little communication among project members, so they are well-suited to an organization that stresses rules, specialization, formality, and a clear definition of organizational hierarchy.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Table 3.5 summarizes the characteristics of projects and the suggested organizational structure to address them.A large project with high certainty and repetition probably needs a highly structured organization",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In contrast, projects with high uncertainty, such as those involving new techniques or changing requirements, benefit from a loosely structured, democratic approach with open communication and participation in decision making.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "On the other hand, when there is much uncertainty involved in a project, a more democratic approach may be better. For example, if the requirements may change as development proceeds, the project has a degree of uncertainty.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Here, participation in decision making, a loosely defined hierarchy, and the encouragement of open communication can be effective.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Regarding work styles of coworkers, typical profiles include:",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "Several typical staff profiles illustrate different work styles",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Kai, a rational extrovert, prioritizes efficiency and quick decision-making, focusing on results and asserting authority when necessary.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Kai, a rational extrovert, judges her colleagues by the results they produce. When making a decision, her top priority is efficiency. Thus, she wants to know only the bottom line. She examines her options and their probable effects, but she does not need to see documents or hear explanations supporting each option. If her time is wasted or her efficiency is hampered in some way, she asserts her authority to regain control of the situation.Thus, Kai is good at making sound decisions quickly.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Marcel, a rational introvert, values thoroughness and accuracy, preferring to make decisions only after gathering complete information.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Marcel, a rational introvert, is very different from his colleague Kai. He judges his peers by how busy they are, and he has little tolerance for those who appear not to be working hard all the time. He is a good worker, admired for the energy he devotes to his work. His reputation as a good worker is very important to him, and he prides himself on being accurate and thorough. He does not like to make decisions without complete information. When asked to make a presentation, Marcel does so only after gathering all relevant information on the subject.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "David, an intuitive extrovert, relies on intuition and professional judgment, enjoys sharing ideas, and prefers a highly interactive work environment.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Marcel shares an office with David, an intuitive extrovert. Whereas Marcel will not make a decision without complete knowledge of the situation, David prefers to follow his feelings. Often, he will trust his intuition about a problem, basing his decision on professional judgment rather than a slow, careful analysis of the information at hand. Since he is assertive, David tends to tell the others on his project about his new ideas. He is creative, and he enjoys when others recognize his ideas. David likes to work in an environment where there is a great deal of interaction among the staff members.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The advantages of a structured organizational approach include timely completion and prevention of scope creep by setting deadlines and breaking tasks into subtasks with individual responsibilities.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "One way she places structure on a team is by encouraging team members to set deadlines. The overall task is broken into small subtasks, and individual team members are responsible for time estimates. The deadlines help to prevent 'scope creep,' the injection of unnecessary functionality into a product.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The structured teams do a Day's Inn [a bland but functional small hotel], but they're finished and putting chairs around the pool when I call time,' she says.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "However, too much structure may limit creativity, as unstructured teams tend to produce more creative but less timely results.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "'The unstructured teams always do incredibly creative, multistoried Taj Mahals and never complete one on time.'",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A balanced approach combining structure and creativity is often recommended, such as allowing egoless programming within a hierarchical structure or imposing hierarchy within loosely structured teams for specific tasks.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The two types of organizational structure can be combined, where appropriate. For instance, programmers may be asked to develop a subsystem on their own, using an egoless approach within a hierarchical structure. Or the test team of a loosely structured project may impose a hierarchical structure on itself and designate one person to be responsible for all major testing decisions.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "One technique for making a prediction for effort is expert judgment, which relies on the experience and competence of managers or experts familiar with similar projects.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Many effort-estimation methods rely on expert judgment. Some are informal techniques, based on a manager's experience with similar projects.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "This prediction can be made early in the development process, either as a top-down or bottom-up analysis of what is needed.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The complete estimate can be computed from either a top-down or a bottom-up analysis of what is needed.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "The prediction may be repeated or refined using techniques such as the Delphi method, where experts make individual predictions, see the average, and revise their estimates until consensus is reached.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The Delphi technique makes use of expert judgment in a different way. Experts are asked to make individual predictions secretly, based on their expertise and using whatever process they choose. Then, the average estimate is calculated and presented to the group. Each expert has the opportunity to revise his or her estimate, if desired. The process is repeated until no expert wants to revise.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Another technique is analogy-based estimation, where effort is predicted by comparing the proposed system to a previously built similar system.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Many times analogies are used to estimate effort. If we have already built a system much like the one proposed, then we can use the similarity as the basis for our estimates.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "This prediction is typically made early in the development process when the proposed system is being planned, and the analogy can be extended proportionally based on size or complexity.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "For example, if system A is similar to system B, then the cost to produce system A should be very much like the cost to produce B. We can extend the analogy to say that if A is about half the size or complexity of B, then A should cost about half as much as B.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Two values that can be calculated from the estimate, E, and the actual value, A, to help determine the accuracy of the estimating process are the acceptance range and the window of error.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "We describe this window by using an acceptance range : a statement of the maximum difference between prediction and actual value.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The acceptance range is defined as the maximum difference allowed between the predicted value and the actual value for the prediction to be considered acceptable. For example, an acceptance range of 20% means that the predicted value should be within 20% of the actual value.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "We describe this window by using an acceptance range : a statement of the maximum difference between prediction and actual value. Thus, 20% is the model's acceptance range.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The window of error refers to the range around the actual value within which the prediction is considered accurate. This window can vary in width depending on the circumstances and the type of prediction system, such as deterministic or stochastic models.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In a stochastic model, we allow for a window of error around the actual value, and the width of the window can vary.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "These values are used to tell us that a prediction is acceptable by stating in advance what range of difference between the estimate and actual value is tolerable. If the difference falls within the acceptance range or window of error, the prediction is considered accurate enough for practical use.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "We must always state in advance what range is acceptable before using a prediction system.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "One size measure is the number of scenario scripts (NSS) in use cases, as described by Lorenz and Kidd (1994).",
        "citations": [
