        "segment": "The advantage of this measure is that it provides a consistent vocabulary throughout development stages, allowing the estimation technique to be reapplied and the estimate inputs to be directly comparable.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The advantage of assessing size in the same terms throughout development is clear: the estimation technique can be reapplied during development, and the estimate inputs are directly comparable.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "A disadvantage is not explicitly mentioned, but it may be less detailed than measures that consider specific aspects of classes or use cases.",
        "citations": [],
        "type": null
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Yes, it is appropriate to specify that the system should not do what it is not intended to do.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A requirement is an expression of desired behavior. A requirement deals with objects or entities, the states they can be in, and the functions that are performed to change states or object characteristics.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Requirements include specific descriptions of functions or characteristics that address the general purpose of the system, which can include limiting entities or defining relationships among entities.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "All of these requirements are specific descriptions of functions or characteristics that address the general purpose of the system: to generate paychecks. Thus, we look for requirements that identify key entities ('an employee is a person who is paid by the company'), limit entities ('an employee may be paid for no more than 40 hours per week'), or define relationships among entities ('employee X is supervised by employee Y if Y can authorize a change to X's salary').",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "For example, a requirement may specify that an employee may be paid for no more than 40 hours per week, which is a way of specifying what the system should not do (i.e., not pay for more than 40 hours).",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "limit entities ('an employee may be paid for no more than 40 hours per week')",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "There are different consumers of software requirements, each using the requirements for different purposes and needing the requirements documented in ways that suit their needs.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In the end, the requirements are used by many different people and for different purposes.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "The main consumers of software requirements and their uses are:",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Requirements analysts and their clients use requirements to explain their understanding of how the system should behave. Designers treat requirements as constraints on what would be considered an acceptable solution. The test team derives from the requirements a suite of acceptance tests , which will be used to demonstrate to the customer that the system being delivered is indeed what was ordered. The maintenance team uses the requirements to help ensure that system enhancements (repairs and new features) do not interfere with the system's original intent.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Requirements analysts and their clients use requirements to explain their understanding of how the system should behave.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Requirements analysts and their clients use requirements to explain their understanding of how the system should behave.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Designers treat requirements as constraints on what would be considered an acceptable solution.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Designers treat requirements as constraints on what would be considered an acceptable solution.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "The test team derives from the requirements a suite of acceptance tests, which will be used to demonstrate to the customer that the system being delivered is indeed what was ordered.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The test team derives from the requirements a suite of acceptance tests , which will be used to demonstrate to the customer that the system being delivered is indeed what was ordered.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "The maintenance team uses the requirements to help ensure that system enhancements (repairs and new features) do not interfere with the system's original intent.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The maintenance team uses the requirements to help ensure that system enhancements (repairs and new features) do not interfere with the system's original intent.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "To make the requirements useful for these different consumers, two kinds of requirements documents are often created:",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Sometimes a single document can serve all of these needs, leading to a common understanding among customers, requirements analysts, and developers. But often two documents are needed: a requirements definition that is aimed at a business audience, such as clients, customers, and users, and a requirements specification that is aimed at a technical audience, such as designers, testers, and project managers.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "These documents are:",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Requirements definition: aimed at a business audience including clients, customers, and users. It is a complete listing of everything the customer wants to achieve, expressed in terms of the environment and describing desired constraints and transformations. It represents a contract describing what functionality the developer promises to deliver.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A requirements definition is a complete listing of everything the customer wants to achieve.The document expresses requirements by describing the entities in the environment in which the proposed system will be installed, and by describing the desired constraints on, monitoring of, or transformations of those entities. The purpose of the proposed system is to realize these requirements (Zave and Jackson 1997). Thus, the requirements are written entirely in terms of the environment, describing how the environment will be affected by the proposed system.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The requirements definition is typically written jointly by the client and the requirements analyst, and it represents a contract describing what functionality the developer promises to deliver to the client.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Requirements specification: aimed at a technical audience such as designers, testers, and project managers. It restates the requirements as a specification of how the proposed system shall behave, written in terms of the system's interface and only referring to environmental entities accessible to the system. It refines the original requirements definition and is used by software developers.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The requirements specification restates the requirements as a specification of how the proposed system shall behave. The specification also is written entirely in terms of the environment, except that it refers solely to environmental entities that are accessible to the system via its interface.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The requirements specification is written by the requirements analyst and is used by the other software developers.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The requirements specification should document the system's interface in detail, including inputs, outputs, data formats, protocols, and timing constraints. It restates the required functionality in terms of the interface's inputs and outputs, possibly using functional notation, data-flow diagrams, state machines, or event traces to illustrate operations.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In documenting the system's interface, we describe all inputs and outputs in detail, including the sources of inputs, the destinations of outputs, the value ranges and data formats of input and output data, protocols governing the order in which certain inputs and outputs must be exchanged, window formats and organization, and any timing constraints.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Next, we restate the required functionality in terms of the interfaces' inputs and outputs. We may use a functional notation or data-flow diagrams to map inputs to outputs, or use logic to document functions' pre-conditions and post-conditions. We may use state machines or event traces to illustrate exact sequences of operations",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Some negative stereotypes customers may hold about developers include that developers don't understand operational needs, can't translate clearly stated needs into a successful system, set unrealistic standards for requirements definition, place too much emphasis on technicalities, are always late, can't respond quickly to legitimately changing needs, are always over budget, say 'no' all the time, try to tell customers how to do their jobs, and ask users for time and effort even to the detriment of the users' important primary duties.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Developers don't understand operational needs. Developers can't translate clearly stated needs into a successful system. Developers set unrealistic standards for requirements definition. Developers place too much emphasis on technicalities. Developers are always late. Developers can't respond quickly to legitimately changing needs. Developers are always over budget. Developers say 'no'all the time. Developers try to tell us how to do our jobs. Developers ask users for time and effort, even to the detriment of the users' important primary duties.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "To minimize the impact of these negative stereotypes, as a developer, you should develop excellent interpersonal skills to understand and address the concerns of each participant, communicate clearly, and manage expectations effectively. Understanding each stakeholder's viewpoint and packaging requirements appropriately for different audiences can help reduce misunderstandings and conflicts.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "One of the many skills of a requirements analyst is the ability to understand each view and capture the requirements in a way that reflects the concerns of each participant. ... good requirements analysis requires excellent interpersonal skills as well as solid technical skills.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The Robertsons' requirements definition template can be a valuable tool for software developers to validate requirements during the requirements process.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A comprehensive requirements-definition template developed by James and Suzanne Robertson can be found at the Web site of the Atlantic Systems Guild: http:// www.systemsguild.com.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The template is most helpful after elicitation and analysis activities, when the requirements have been gathered and understood, and the developer is ready to document and validate the requirements.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "[FIGURE 4.1 Process for capturing the requirements.] Elicitation, Analysis, Specification, Validation",
                "img_id": "img0_se_theory_practice.pdf__chunk_1291_1291_306"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "To use the template effectively for validating requirements, the developer must work closely with users, customers, testers, designers, and other team members to ensure the requirements documents describe the problem clearly and leave solution selection to the designers.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "requirements activities should not be performed by the software developer in isolation: definition and specification efforts require working closely with users, customers, testers, designers, and other team members.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The developer should have skills in describing requirements in terms of environmental phenomena, distinguishing between functional and quality requirements, and using a combination of specification techniques to cover different aspects of the system.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "It is essential that the requirements definition and specification documents describe the problem, leaving solution selection to the designers. The best way of ensuring that you do not stray into the solution space is to describe requirements and specifications in terms of environmental phenomena.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "There are both functional and quality requirements to keep in mind. The functional requirements explain what the system will do, and the quality requirements constrain solutions in terms of safety, reliability, budget, schedule, and so on.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "There are many different types of definition and specification techniques. Some are descriptive, such as entity-relationship diagrams and logic, while others are behavioral, such as event traces, data-flow diagrams, and functions. Some have graphical notations, and some are based on mathematics. Each emphasizes a different view of the problem, and suggests different criteria for decomposing a problem into subproblems. It is often desirable to use a combination of techniques to specify the different aspects of a system.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Using the template helps uncover errors and faults related to unclear or incomplete requirements, mixing problem description with solution details, and missing quality or design constraints, thus ensuring the requirements are well-defined and validated before proceeding to design and implementation.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The functional requirements define the boundaries of the solution space for our problem. ... it is usually not enough for a software product to compute correct outputs; there are other types of requirements that also distinguish between acceptable and unacceptable products. A quality requirement, or nonfunctional requirement, describes some quality characteristic that the software solution must possess, such as fast response time, ease of use, high reliability, or low maintenance costs. A design constraint is a design decision, such as choice of platform or interface components, that has already been made and that restricts the set of solutions to our problem.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "One of the categories Pamela Zave presents in her classification scheme for research in software requirements is the development of specification techniques and tools that permit easier ways to prove assumptions and assertions, and to demonstrate consistency, completeness, and determinism.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Develop specification techniques and tools that permit easier ways to prove assumptions and assertions,and to demonstrate consistency,completeness,and determinism",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Research in this area is of great use to software developers because it helps ensure that the requirements specifications are precise and unambiguous, reducing errors and misunderstandings early in the development process. This leads to more reliable software systems and can reduce costly rework later in the development lifecycle.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Develop specification techniques and tools that permit easier ways to prove assumptions and assertions,and to demonstrate consistency,completeness,and determinism",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Module “InventorySearchByID” is likely to have a high degree of cohesion because it performs a single, well-defined function: searching the records in inventory for matching IDs and returning the results.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Our ideal is functional cohesion , where two conditions hold: all elements essential to a single function are contained in one module, and all of that module's elements are essential to the performance of that function. A functionally cohesive module performs only the function for which it is designed, and nothing else.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Module “ProcessPurchase” is likely to have a low degree of cohesion because it performs multiple unrelated functions: removing the product from inventory, printing a receipt, and updating the log.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A module that serves multiple purposes is at greater risk of its elements needing to evolve in different ways or at different rates.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A module has logical cohesion if its parts are related only by the logic structure of its code. As an example, consider a template module or procedure that performs very different operations depending on the values of its parameters.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Module “FindSet” is likely to have a low degree of cohesion because it combines processing the user's request, determining the matching set, and formatting the list, which are different operations that may evolve separately.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A module that serves multiple purposes is at greater risk of its elements needing to evolve in different ways or at different rates.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A module has logical cohesion if its parts are related only by the logic structure of its code.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A design review is described as “egoless” because the criticism and discussion during the review are directed at the process and the product, not at the participants themselves.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The criticism and discussion during the design review are egoless, because comments are directed at the process and the product, not at the participants.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Egoless reviews are necessary because they emphasize that everyone involved is working toward the same goal, which encourages open communication and collaboration among diverse team members.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "It is important to remember that those who participate in the review are investigating the integrity of the design, not of the designers. Thus, the review is valuable in emphasizing to all concerned that we are working toward the same goal. The criticism and discussion during the design review are egoless, because comments are directed at the process and the product, not at the participants. The review process encourages and enhances communication among the diverse members of the team.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "Steps that may help achieve egoless reviews include:",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Direct comments and criticism at the design and process rather than at individuals.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The criticism and discussion during the design review are egoless, because comments are directed at the process and the product, not at the participants.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Encourage open communication and collaboration among all team members.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The review process encourages and enhances communication among the diverse members of the team.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Focus on detecting faults early when they are easy and inexpensive to correct, rather than assigning blame.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Moreover, the process benefits everyone by finding faults and problems when they are easy and inexpensive to correct.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Consider a software system such as a billing application used in a service station, where the user interface includes buttons and text boxes for input.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "For example, the lefthand side of Figure 6.37 shows the paper bill that Manny uses at the Royal Service Station. Now, to automate his billing process, we may suggest a screen like the one on the right-hand side. If Manny agrees to the screen design, the next step involves designing one or more classes to implement the screen. We may decide to use the design shown in Figure 6.38. Notice that this design includes classes for an okay button and a text box.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A disliked feature might be that the interface is not intuitive or flexible enough, making it difficult to perform tasks efficiently or causing frustration due to poor layout or lack of customization.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Most aspects of user-interface design are about how information is presented to and collected from the user. These design decisions tend not to be architectural, so we postpone a detailed discussion of this topic until the next chapter.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "This problem could have been avoided during design by involving the users more closely in the design process, defining scenarios for each way the system can perform a task, and refining the sequence of user interactions with the system.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Let us look more closely at designing a user interface. We must consider several issues: identifying the humans who will interact with the system, defining scenarios for each way that the system can perform a task, designing a hierarchy of user commands, refining the sequence of user interactions with the system.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Changes to the design process that would be necessary include laying out the interaction on paper early, integrating user-interface classes into the overall system class hierarchy, and maintaining design flexibility to accommodate evolving user needs.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The first step in user-interface design is laying out the interaction on paper. ... This expansion of classes and hierarchy is another important reason to consider design flexibility as we devise our solution.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A detailed discussion of design patterns can be found in the work by Gamma et al. (1995), which originally identified a set of design patterns and their purposes.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The original design patterns identified by Gamma et al. (1995) are listed in Table 6.4, along with the purpose of each.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "One example of a design pattern is a pattern that encapsulates a particular type of design decision, such as the choice of algorithm that implements an operation or the type of object instantiated.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "each pattern is designed to encapsulate a particular type of design decision. The decision types vary widely, from the choice of algorithm that implements an operation to the type of object instantiated to the order in which a collection of objects is traversed.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Design patterns are useful for improving a design's modularity and can be used to make future design changes easier to implement or to enable a program to change its structure or behavior at runtime.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The main goal of design patterns is to improve a design's modularity. In fact, each pattern is designed to encapsulate a particular type of design decision. Some design patterns structure a design to make future design changes easier to implement. Other patterns enable a program to change its structure or behavior at runtime.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Using design patterns often involves substantial use of interfaces, information hiding, and polymorphism, and they introduce a level of indirection which can add complexity to the design.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Design patterns make substantial use of interfaces, information hiding, and polymorphism, and they often introduce a level of indirection in a clever way.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The added complexity from design patterns can sometimes make the design seem overly complicated, which may affect other quality attributes such as performance or ease of development.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Because the patterns add extra classes, associations, and method calls, they sometimes can seem overly complicated. This complexity improves modularity, even at the expense of other quality attributes such as performance or ease of development.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Therefore, design patterns are most useful in situations where the extra flexibility and modularity they provide are worth the additional cost and complexity required to implement them.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "For this reason, the patterns are useful only in situations where the extra flexibility is worth the extra cost required to implement them.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The Therac-25 accidents highlight several important lessons for software design in safety-critical systems.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Leveson and Turner (1993) describe how the underlying cause of the problems was a timing error that was difficult to reproduce.",
                "img_id": null
