    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "Key lessons include",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Documentation should be done as development progresses, not afterward.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Documentation should be done as development progresses, not afterward.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Software quality assurance practices should be an integral part of the development process, including early standards and evaluation of intermediate products.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Software quality assurance practices should be an integral part of the development process. These practices should include standards that are set early and used to evaluate intermediate products.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Simple designs are easier to understand, code, and test than complex ones.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "- Simple designs are easier to understand, code, and test than complex ones.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Software should be designed to anticipate failures and capture information about them.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "- Software should be designed to anticipate failures and capture information about them.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "It is not enough to assume that system testing will catch software problems; software should be tested extensively and subjected to formal analysis at both component and system levels before hardware integration.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "- It is not enough to assume that system testing will catch software problems. Software should be tested extensively, as well as subjected to formal analysis, at the component and system levels before integration with the hardware.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The Object-Oriented characteristics of encapsulation and information hiding support reuse by providing considerable flexibility in encapsulating design decisions and in modifying and reusing designs.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Both the separation of object instances from instance variables and of interfaces from class definitions give us considerable flexibility in encapsulating design decisions and in modifying and reusing designs.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "Encapsulation allows a composite class to manipulate its object-based attributes only through their interfaces without knowing their implementations, which supports modularity and easy replacement of components as long as the replacement complies with the same interface.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "An advantage of object composition is its support of modularity; the composite class knows nothing about the implementations of its object-based attributes and can manipulate these attributes only by using their interfaces. As such, we can easily replace one class component with another, as long as the replacement complies with the same interface.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In deciding whether to reuse a class in a new system, one should consider if the effort to understand and modify the component is less than the effort to write a new equivalent component, and whether the class can be tailored easily with parameters without needing to understand its internals.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Clear-box reuse (sometimes called white-box reuse ) is more common but still controversial, because the effort to understand and modify the component must be less than the effort to write a new equivalent component. To address this problem, many reusable components are being built with many parameters, making them easier to tailor with an external view, rather than forcing developers to understand the internals.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "It is useful to have separate phases for system and program design because the system's architectural design focuses on identifying major software units and their interfaces, which allows the design of individual software units to be treated as independent tasks.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The architecture also specifies any protocols that constrain how the units interact with each other, and specifies a precise interface for each unit. Moreover, the architectural design process has already resolved and documented any known issues about data sharing and about coordination and synchronization of concurrent components. Of course, some of these decisions may change when we learn more about designing the individual software units. But at this point, the system's design is complete enough to allow us to treat the designing of the various units as independent tasks.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Separating the architecture-design phase from the module-design phase is convenient for project management because it allows design tasks that require consideration of the entire system to be distinguished from those that pertain to individual software units, which can be partitioned into distinct work assignments and assigned to separate design teams.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "for the purposes of project management, it is convenient to separate design tasks that require consideration of the entire system from design tasks that pertain to individual software units, because the latter can be partitioned into distinct work assignments and assigned to separate design teams.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "This separation enables parallelization of the design work, making the process more efficient.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Thus, the more we can restrict ourselves during the architecture-design phase to identifying the major software units and their interfaces, the more we can parallelize the rest of the design work.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "It is important if two different terms are being used to refer to the same entity because this can cause confusion and inconsistency in the requirements and design.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The simplicity of ER notations is deceptive; in fact, it is quite difficult to use ER modeling notations well in practice. It is not always obvious at what level of detail to model a particular problem, even though there are only three major language constructs. For example, should the barrier and coin slot be modeled as entities, or should they be represented by a more abstract turnstile entity? Also, it can be difficult to decide what data are entities and what data are attributes. For example, should the lock be an entity? There are arguments for and against each of these choices. The primary criteria for making decisions are whether a choice results in a clearer description, and whether a choice unnecessarily constrains design decisions."
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Using consistent terminology helps to describe and reason about the system clearly from requirements through design to code, enabling better communication, traceability, and understanding among the development team.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The design process describes the system components using a common language with which to communicate. Object orientation is a particularly appealing basis for such design, because it allows us to describe and reason about the system from its birth to its delivery in the same terms: classes, objects, and methods. This consistency of terminology enables you to anticipate the size and structure of a system well before the design is complete. It simplifies the traceability across artifacts; you can see how a domain object in the requirements becomes an object in the design and then an object in the code, for instance."
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Using inheritance to create separate classes for each service as subclasses of a general “sale item” class allows you to reuse and extend the definitions of the existing class.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Alternatively, we can build new classes by extending or modifying definitions of existing classes. This kind of construction, called inheritance, defines a new class by directly reusing (and adding to) the definitions of an existing class.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "This means you only need to provide definitions that distinguish each subclass from the parent class, such as specific attributes or methods unique to purchasing or rebinding services.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "If we define Bulk Sale as an extension of our regular Sale class, then we need to provide only the definitions that distinguish Bulk Sale from its parent class, Sale.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "Inheritance also supports polymorphism, allowing code to interact with the general sale item interface while the actual behavior depends on the specific subclass at runtime.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Object orientation also supports polymorphism, whereby code is written in terms of interactions with an interface, but code behavior depends on the object associated with the interface at runtime and on the implementations of that object's methods.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "However, there are arguments against using inheritance in this case. Inheritance can increase dependencies among classes, requiring knowledge of all parent and subclass interfaces and potentially complicating maintenance when any class changes.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In our sales transaction example, consider a new class Bill that generates an invoice each month... our Bill class accesses and thus depends directly on CustomerAccount, Sale, and Item classes. We must know the interfaces of all of them to invoke the appropriate methods correctly. Worse, we have to recheck our implementation whenever any of these classes is changed.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "Additionally, wrapper classes can be used to add functionality without changing existing classes, but they may complicate design and degrade runtime performance.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "On the downside, such designs often use a wrapper class to add functionality without changing the implementations of existing classes... they can complicate the design and degrade runtime performance.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Factors influencing the decision include trade-offs among design complexity, development time, runtime performance, fault avoidance, and ease of maintenance.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Thus, deciding whether to adhere to the Law of Demeter involves evaluating trade-offs among design complexity, development time, runtime performance, fault avoidance, and ease of maintenance.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A class that is deeper in the inheritance hierarchy is likely harder to understand and maintain because it inherits attributes and methods from a larger collection of ancestor classes.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "the larger the depth of the class's inheritance (i.e., attributes and methods are inherited from a larger collection of ancestor classes, thus the class is harder to understand)",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "This increased inheritance makes the class more complex and harder to maintain.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "the deeper a class is in the hierarchy, the more methods it is likely to inherit. This characteristic makes the class harder to understand and harder to maintain.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "To implement a stack data structure using an array with a maximum capacity of 100 elements, you can define an array of integers and maintain an index to track the top of the stack.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The stack supports the following operations:",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "empty operation",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The empty operation returns true if there are no elements in the stack, false otherwise.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "full operation",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The full operation returns true if the stack is filled to capacity, false otherwise.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "push operation",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The push operation takes an element as an argument and places the element on top of the stack, if the stack is not full. If the stack is full, the push operation returns an error.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "pop operation",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The pop operation removes an element from the top of the stack, if the stack is not empty. If the stack is empty, the pop operation returns an error, otherwise, the top element is returned.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "top operation",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The top operation returns the element on the top of the stack without removing the element from the stack, if the stack is not empty. The top operation returns an error if the stack is empty.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A simple implementation outline in pseudocode is as follows:",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Initialize an array of size 100 to hold the stack elements.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Maintain an integer variable top initialized to -1 to indicate the stack is empty.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "empty() returns true if top == -1, false otherwise.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "full() returns true if top == 99, false otherwise.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "push(element) checks if the stack is full; if not, increments top and assigns the element to array[top]; otherwise, returns an error.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "pop() checks if the stack is empty; if not, returns array[top] and decrements top; otherwise, returns an error.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "top() checks if the stack is empty; if not, returns array[top] without modifying top; otherwise, returns an error.",
