[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The relationship between design and implementation is critical because the program code components must directly correspond to the program design components.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The most critical standard is the need for a direct correspondence between the program design components and the program code components.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "It is important to match the implementation to the design because the design's modularity, such as low coupling, high cohesion, and well-defined interfaces, should be carried forward into the code to ensure that algorithms, functions, interfaces, and data structures can be traced easily from design to code and back again.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Design characteristics, such as low coupling, high cohesion, and well-defined interfaces, should also be program characteristics, so that the algorithms, functions, interfaces, and data structures can be traced easily from design to code and back again.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Matching design and implementation is essential because the system's nature may change over time with enhancements and modifications, and these changes are made first to the high-level design and then traced through lower design levels to the code that must be modified.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "These changes are made first to the high-level design and then are traced through lower design levels to the code that must be modified. Thus, the correspondence between design and code is essential.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Without this correspondence, testing, maintenance, and configuration management become impossible.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In later chapters, we will see that testing, maintenance, and configuration management are impossible without the links established by these standards.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "To keep design and implementation consistent, one should use a common language and consistent terminology across requirements, design, and code, such as object orientation with classes, objects, and methods, which simplifies traceability and understanding of the system.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The design process describes the system components using a common language with which to communicate. Object orientation is a particularly appealing basis for such design, because it allows us to describe and reason about the system from its birth to its delivery in the same terms: classes, objects, and methods. This consistency of terminology enables you to anticipate the size and structure of a system well before the design is complete. It simplifies the traceability across artifacts; you can see how a domain object in the requirements becomes an object in the design and then an object in the code, for instance.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Additionally, producing clear design documentation that reflects a top-down design process helps other designers, programmers, maintainers, testers, and specialists understand the design and maintain consistency between design and implementation.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The process we use to work towards a final solution is not as important as the documentation we produce so that other designers can understand it. This understanding is crucial not only for the programmers who will implement the design but also for the maintainers who will change it, the testers and reviewers who will ensure that the design implements the requirements, and the specialists who will write user documentation describing how the system works.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "One way to achieve this understanding is by 'faking the rational design process': writing the design documentation to reflect a topdown design process, even if this is not how we arrived at the design.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The kind of reuse where you use code written by someone else is called consumer reuse.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Some companies have division-wide or company-wide reuse programs, with standards for evaluating and changing components; Sidebar 7.2 describes such a program at Lucent. The success of these programs suggests reuse",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "There are two kinds of reuse: producer reuse, where we are creating components designed to be reused in subsequent applications, and consumer reuse, where we are using components that were originally developed for other projects (Barnes and Bollinger 1991).",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Problems encountered in consumer reuse include verifying that the reused module performs its required function acceptably and ensuring it is failure-free.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "An important issue in black-box reuse is our ability to verify that a reused module performs its required function in an acceptable way. If the component is code, we want to be sure it is failure-free;",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "To resolve these problems, one should carefully evaluate the reused components to ensure they meet the required quality and functionality before integrating them into the new system.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Reuse requires us to evaluate products from current and former development projects, to determine if they are the type and quality that we want for the next system we will be building.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Guidelines that may help eliminate or mitigate problems include revising and rewriting code rather than patching, reexamining the design if control flow or decision processes are convoluted, and maintaining links among requirements, design, and code.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Revising and Rewriting, Not Patching. When writing code, as when preparing a term paper or creating a work of art, you often write a rough draft. Then you carefully revise and rewrite until you are satisfied with the result. If you find the control flow convoluted, or the decision processes hard to understand, or the unconditional branches difficult to eliminate, then it may be time to return to the design. Reexamine the design to see whether the problems you are encountering are inherent in the design or in your translation to code. Look again at how the data are represented and structured, at the algorithms chosen, and at the decomposition.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Thus, pseudocode has acted as a framework on which to construct the code. In briefing the code from the design in this way, notice that the design's organization has changed several times. Such changes must be reported to and approved by the designers, so that the links among requirements, design, and code can be documented and maintained.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "When writing code, it is essential to follow coding standards and procedures to ensure clarity, maintainability, and effective collaboration among team members.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "many people are usually involved, and a great deal of cooperation and coordination is required. Thus, it is very important for others to be able to understand not only what you have written, but also why you have written it and how it fits in with their work.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Below is a set of coding standards for Python, chosen to promote readability, maintainability, and ease of collaboration:",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "Coding standards for Python include",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Use clear and descriptive names for variables, functions, and classes to make the code self-explanatory.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "if the data names are clear and the interfaces well-defined, the maintenance programmer can be sure that the change needed will not have any unexpected effects on other parts of the code.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Include a header comment block at the beginning of each program or module describing its functions and interfaces with other programs.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "a separate team may test the code. Or another set of people may integrate your software with other programs to build and test subsystems and finally the whole system. ... suppose every program produced by your company begins with a section describing the program's functions and interfaces with other programs.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Document the code internally with comments explaining the purpose of complex sections and the rationale behind design decisions.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Some of the procedures involve methods of documenting your code so that it is clear and easy to follow. Such documentation allows you to leave and return to your work without losing track of what you had been doing.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Follow consistent formatting and style guidelines, such as indentation and spacing, to enhance readability.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Many companies insist that their code conform to style, format, and content standards, so that the code and associated documentation are clear to everyone who reads them.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Use modular design and information hiding to reveal only essential information about components, facilitating reuse and maintenance.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Your use of information hiding allows you to reveal only the essential information about your components so that your colleagues can invoke them or reuse them.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Incorporate a systemwide error-handling strategy to manage faults effectively.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "incorporating a systemwide error-handling strategy",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "These standards are included because they help organize code clearly, make it easier for others to understand and maintain, and support teamwork by ensuring consistent communication through code and documentation.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Standards and procedures can help you to organize your thoughts and avoid mistakes. Some of the procedures involve methods of documenting your code so that it is clear and easy to follow. Such documentation allows you to leave and return to your work without losing track of what you had been doing. Standardized documentation also helps in locating faults and making changes, because it clarifies which sections of your program perform which functions.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Your use of standards enhances communication among team members.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "To classify faults from code, you can use a defect classification scheme such as IBM's Orthogonal Defect Classification or Hewlett-Packard's fault classification.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Chillarege et al. (1992) at IBM have developed an approach to fault tracking called orthogonal defect classification, where faults are placed in categories that collectively paint a picture of which parts of the development process need attention because they are responsible for spawning many faults.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Grady (1997) describes Hewlett-Packard's approach to fault classification. In 1986, Hewlett-Packard's Software Metrics Council identified several categories in which to track faults.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "IBM's Orthogonal Defect Classification categorizes faults into types such as Function, Interface, Checking, Assignment, Timing/serialization, Build/package/merge, Documentation, and Algorithm.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "TABLE 8.1 IBM Orthogonal Defect Classification: FaultType - Function: Fault that affects capability, end-user interfaces, product interfaces, interface with hardware architecture, or global data structure; Interface: Fault in interacting with other components or drivers via calls, macros, control blocks, or parameter lists; Checking: Fault in program logic that fails to validate data and values properly before they are used; Assignment: Fault in data structure or code block initialization; Timing/serialization: Fault that involves timing of shared and real-time resources; Build/package/merge: Fault that occurs because of problems in repositories, management changes, or version control; Documentation: Fault that affects publications and maintenance notes; Algorithm: Fault involving efficiency or correctness of algorithm or data structure but not design.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Hewlett-Packard's fault classification includes categories based on the origin of the fault (such as Specification/requirements, Design, Code, Environment/support, Documentation, Other) and the mode of the fault (Missing, Unclear, Wrong, Changed, Better way).",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Hewlett-Packard's Software Metrics Council identified several categories in which to track faults. The scheme grew to be the one depicted in Figure 8.1. The developers use this model by selecting three descriptors for each fault found: the origin of the fault (i.e., where the fault was injected in a product), the type of fault, and the mode (i.e., whether information was missing, unclear, wrong, changed, or could be done a better way).",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "img",
                "content": null,
                "img_id": "img0_se_theory_practice.pdf__chunk_3348_3350_803"
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "When classifying faults, it is important to ensure orthogonality, meaning each fault should belong to exactly one category to avoid ambiguity and maintain meaningful summary information.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "One of the key features of orthogonal defect classification is its orthogonality. That is, a classification scheme is orthogonal if any item being classified belongs to exactly one category. In other words, we want to track the faults in our system in an unambiguous way, so that the summary information about the number of faults in each class is meaningful.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Difficulties in classifying faults may include deciding whether a fault is a fault of omission (something missing) or commission (something incorrect), and ensuring consistent classification among different developers.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "When using the classification, the developers identify not only the type of fault, but also whether it is a fault of omission or commission. A fault of omission is one that results when some key aspect of the code is missing; for example, a fault may occur when a variable is not initialized. A fault of commission is one that is incorrect; for example, the variable is initialized to the wrong value.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The fault classification must be clear, so that any two developers are likely to classify a particular fault in the same way.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The type of fault that occurred most frequently is logic faults, which accounted for 32% of the faults in one Hewlett-Packard division.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "img",
                "content": null,
                "img_id": "img0_se_theory_practice.pdf__chunk_3352_3353_804"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "To reduce the occurrence of logic faults, software development approaches should include thorough design reviews and code inspections focused on logic computation and data handling.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "IBM's use of this concept by showing us that the fault profile for design review is very different from that for code inspection.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Finally, the code should be reviewed to confirm that organizational standards and procedures have been followed.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Additionally, following organizational standards and procedures carefully can help prevent faults that make the code difficult to understand or modify, which indirectly reduces fault introduction.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Standards and procedure faults may not always affect the running of the programs, but they may foster an environment where faults are created as the system is tested and modified.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Unit testing focuses on verifying that individual components or units of code work correctly and meet their objectives.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "When we are satisfied that individual components are working correctly and meet our objectives, we combine them into a working system.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The goal of unit testing is to ensure that the code implements the design properly, meaning that the programmers wrote code to do what the designers intended.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The objective of unit and integration testing was to ensure that the code implemented the design properly; that is, that the programmers wrote code to do what the designers intended.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Integration testing occurs after unit testing when individual components are combined into a working system to verify that the components work together correctly.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "When we are satisfied that individual components are working correctly and meet our objectives, we combine them into a working system.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The goal of integration testing is to test the interactions between components and to identify failures caused by the combination of components.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "This integration is planned and coordinated so that when a failure occurs, we have some idea of what caused it.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Unit testing should occur first, focusing on individual components, and integration testing should follow, combining components in a planned and coordinated manner.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "When we are satisfied that individual components are working correctly and meet our objectives, we combine them into a working system.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Integration testing is a team activity that requires coordination among team members to choose an integration strategy, plan tests, generate test cases, and run tests.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Integration testing is a team activity, too, and you must coordinate with other team members in choosing an integration strategy, planning your tests, generating test cases, and running the tests.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Unit testing is typically done on individual components in isolation, while integration testing involves combining components according to a strategy that may be top-down, bottom-up, or a combination.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The system is again viewed as a hierarchy of components, where each component belongs to a layer of the design. We can begin from the top and work our way down as we test, work from the bottom up, or use a combination of these two approaches.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Object-oriented testing differs from traditional testing in several key ways related to the nature of objects and their interactions.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Graham (1996a) summarizes the differences between object-oriented and traditional testing in two ways.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "Aspects that make object-oriented testing easier include",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "objects tend to be small, and the complexity that might ordinarily reside in the component is often pushed instead toward the interfaces among components.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Unit testing is less difficult because objects are small.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "objects tend to be small, and the complexity that might ordinarily reside in the component is often pushed instead toward the interfaces among components.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "However, object-oriented testing is harder in these ways:",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "integration testing must be much more extensive. As we have seen, encapsulation is often considered a positive attribute of object-oriented design, but it also requires more extensive integration testing.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Integration testing is more extensive due to encapsulation and complex interfaces.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "integration testing must be much more extensive. As we have seen, encapsulation is often considered a positive attribute of object-oriented design, but it also requires more extensive integration testing.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Inheritance requires retesting of inherited methods when subclasses are added or modified.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "when we add a new subclass or modify an existing subclass, we must retest the methods inherited from each of its ancestor superclasses.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Overriding methods in subclasses must be retested with possibly different test data.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "When a subclass replaces an inherited method with a locally defined method with the same name, the overriding subclass must be retested, and probably with a different set of test data.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Traditional metrics like cyclomatic complexity are less useful for object-oriented systems.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Most source code measurements are defined for procedural code, not for objects and methods. Traditional metrics such as cyclomatic numbers are of little use when assessing the size and complexity of object-oriented systems.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Code coverage measurements and tools are less valuable because complexity arises from object interactions.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Because it is the interaction of objects that is the source of complexity, code coverage measurements and tools are of less value in object-oriented testing than in traditional testing.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Requirements validation and test case generation tools are less prepared for object-oriented models.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "- Requirements are likely to be expressed in the requirements document, but there are few tools to support validation of requirements expressed as objects and methods.\n- Likewise, most tools that assist in test case generation are not prepared to handle a model expressed in objects and methods.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Consider the example code illustrated in Figure 8.7, which has statements numbered 1 through 7.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "To see how the strategy affects the number of test cases, consider the example in Figure 8.7, which illustrates the logic flow in a component to be tested. Each statement, represented by a diamond or rectangle, has been numbered.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "img",
                "content": null,
                "img_id": "img0_se_theory_practice.pdf__chunk_3498_3504_836"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "For statement testing, test cases must execute every statement at least once. In this example, one test case suffices by choosing X larger than K to produce a positive RESULT, which executes statements 1 through 7 in order.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Statement testing requires test cases that execute statements 1 through 7. By choosing X larger than K that produces a positive RESULT, we can execute statements in order, so one test case suffices.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "For all-uses testing, the test set must include at least one path from every definition to every use that can be reached by that definition. This is a data-flow testing strategy that follows each data item through the component, verifying changes in data values.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "All-uses testing: The test set includes at least one path from every definition to every use that can be reached by that definition.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Because the Piccadilly system is an information system, we may in fact prefer to use a data-flow testing strategy rather than a structural one. Strategies such as definition-use testing may be the most appropriate; we follow each data item through a component, looking for situations where the value of the data element can change, and verifying that the change is correct.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Regarding the strength and number of test cases required, all-uses testing is stronger than statement testing and requires more test cases. Statement testing requires fewer test cases than branch testing, which in turn requires fewer cases than path testing. All-uses testing is stronger than branch testing and random testing, as it found 90% of faults compared to 85.5% for branch testing and 79.5% for random testing.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In our example, statement testing requires fewer test cases than branch testing, which in turn requires fewer cases than path testing.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "He found that random testing found 79.5% of the faults, branch testing found 85.5%, and all-uses testing found 90%.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "System testing differs from unit and integration testing in its objective and focus.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The objective of unit and integration testing was to ensure that the code implemented the design properly; that is, that the programmers wrote code to do what the designers intended.In system testing, we have a very different objective: to ensure that the system does what the customer wants it to do.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Unit testing verifies that individual components function properly in isolation, while integration testing ensures that components work together as described in the design specifications.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "First, each program component is tested on its own, isolated from the other components in the system. Such testing, known as module testing , component testing , or unit  testing , verifies  that  the component functions properly with the types of input expected from studying the component's design.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Integration testing is the process of verifying that the system components work together as described in the system and program design specifications.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "System testing evaluates the integrated system from the customer's perspective to ensure it meets the functional requirements and performs as expected in the actual working environment.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Once we are sure that information is passed among components in accordance with the design, we test the system to ensure that it has the desired functionality.A function test evaluates the system to determine if the functions described by the requirements specification are actually performed by the integrated system.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "When the test is performed successfully in a customer's actual working environment, it yields a validated system .",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Unlike unit and integration testing, system testing is more of a closed-box approach focusing on what the system is supposed to do rather than how it is structured internally.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "System testing begins with function testing. Whereas previous tests concentrated on components and their interactions, this first step ignores system structure and focuses on functionality.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Our approach from now on is more closed box than open.We need not know which component is being executed; rather, we must know what the system is supposed to do.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Function testing checks that the integrated system performs its functions as specified in the requirements, ensuring that the system functions correctly according to the functional requirements.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A function test checks that the integrated system performs its functions as specified in the requirements.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "functional testing addresses the functional requirements",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Performance testing examines how well the system performs its functions in terms of nonfunctional requirements such as speed, accuracy, and accessibility, and is designed and administered by the test team with results provided to the customer.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Performance testing examines how well the calculation is done; the speed of response to user commands, accuracy of the result, and accessibility of the data are checked against the customer's performance prescriptions.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "performance testing addresses the nonfunctional requirements.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Acceptance testing is performed jointly with the customer to ensure that the system works according to the customer's requirements description and that the system is accepted by the customer.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "We join the customer to perform an acceptance test, where the system is checked against the customer's requirements description.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Installation testing is conducted after the system is installed in the environment where it will be used to ensure that the system still functions as it should in its final operational environment.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Upon completion of acceptance testing, the accepted system is installed in the environment in which it will be used; a final installation test is run to make sure that the system still functions as it should.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Verification and validation are two distinct processes used to ensure the quality and correctness of requirements and system development.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In requirements validation, we check that our requirements definition accurately reflects the customer's-actually, all of the stakeholders'needs. Validation is tricky because there are only a few documents that we can use as the basis for arguing that the requirements definitions are correct. In verification, we check that one document or artifact conforms to another. Thus, we verify that our code conforms to our design, and that our design conforms to our requirements specification; at the requirements level, we verify that our requirements specification conforms to the requirements definition. To summarize, verification ensures that we build the system right, whereas validation ensures that we build the right system!",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Verification ensures that the system is built correctly according to the specifications, while validation ensures that the correct system is built according to the stakeholders' needs.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "To summarize, verification ensures that we build the system right, whereas validation ensures that we build the right system!",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Types of testing that address verification include cross-referencing, simulation, consistency checks, completeness checks, and checks for unreachable states or transitions.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Verification | Cross-referencing Simulation Consistency checks Completeness checks Checks for unreachable states or transitions",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Types of testing that address validation include walkthroughs, reading, interviews, reviews, checklists, models to check functions and relationships, scenarios, prototypes, simulation, and formal inspections.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Validation | Walkthroughs Reading Interviews Reviews Checklists Models to check functions and relationships Scenarios Prototypes Simulation Formal inspections",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The Cleanroom software development process, proposed by IBM researchers in the mid-1980s, is designed to produce high-quality software with a high-productivity team by focusing on certifying the software with respect to specifications rather than relying on unit testing to find faults.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The cleanroom approach addresses two fundamental principles: to certify the software with respect to the specifications, rather than wait for unit testing to find the faults; to produce zero-fault or near-zero-fault software",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Cleanroom applies these principles by using box structures to specify software, defining the system as a black box, then refining it as a state box and a clear box, which helps find omissions in requirements early in the life cycle.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "First, software is specified using box structures, introduced in Chapter 8. The system is defined as a black box, refined as a state box, and refined again as a clear box. The box structures encourage analysts to find omissions in requirements early in the life cycle, when they are easier and cheaper to fix.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The clear-box specification is then converted to an intended function expressed in natural language or mathematics, and a correctness theorem defines the correctness of each intended function with respect to its control structures.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Next, the clear-box specification is converted to an intended function, expressed in natural language or in mathematics, as appropriate. A correctness theorem defines a relationship, expressed as one of three correctness conditions, that describes the correctness of each intended function with respect to its control structures.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Cleanroom differs from conventional testing primarily by relying on statistical usage testing based on operational scenarios instead of unit testing, and by separating development and test teams and using peer review.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "- separation of the development and test teams; reliance on peer review instead of unit testing; use of informal state machines and functions to define the system design; statistical testing based on operational scenarios",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Statistical usage testing randomizes test cases based on probability of usage and is considered more effective at improving overall software reliability than traditional coverage testing, which finds faults in random order.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The final step involves statistical usage testing, where test cases are randomized based on probability of usage... Cobb and Mills (1990) report that statistical usage testing is more than 20 times as effective at extending MTTF than is coverage testing.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Unlike conventional testing, Cleanroom avoids unit testing entirely, which has been criticized as potentially dangerous because bugs cannot be found without executing the code that contains them; instead, it relies on statistical testing to verify reliability.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Beizer (1997) suggests that we read the results with caution. He claims that cleanroom's lack of unit testing promotes dangerous malpractice, contradicting 'known testing theory and common sense.' According to Beizer, 'you cannot find a bug unless you execute the code that has the bug,' and orthodox cleanroom relies only on statistical testing to verify reliability, shunning unit testing of any kind.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The Ariane-5 flight control system was tested in four ways: equipment testing, on-board computer software testing, staged integration, and system validation tests.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "According to Lions et al. (1996), the flight control system was tested in four ways: - equipment testing - on-board computer software testing - staged integration - system validation tests",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "However, the testing during software qualification did not discover the SRI problems before the actual flight because no test was performed to verify that the SRI would behave correctly when subjected to the countdown and flight time sequence and the trajectory of Ariane-5.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The investigators reported that 'no test was performed to verify that the SRI would behave correctly when being subjected to the count-down and flight time sequence and the trajectory of Ariane-5' (Lions et al. 1996).",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The specification for the SRI software did not contain the Ariane-5 trajectory data among its functional requirements, and there was no discussion in the requirements documents of the ways in which the Ariane-5 trajectory would be different from Ariane-4.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In fact, the specification for the SRI software did not contain the Ariane-5 trajectory data among its functional requirements. In other words, there was no discussion in the requirements documents of the ways in which the Ariane-5 trajectory would be different from Ariane-4.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The failure was caused by software that continued computations based on Ariane-4 requirements that were not needed for Ariane-5, and the erroneous data from the SRI2 system was interpreted as flight data, leading to the shutdown of both inertial reference systems.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The error occurred in a software module that computed meaningful results only before lift-off. As soon as the launcher lifted off, the function performed by this module served no useful purpose, so it was no longer needed by the rest of the system. However, the module continued its computations for approximately 40 seconds of flight based on a requirement for the Ariane-4 that was not needed for Ariane-5.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The angle of attack was determined by software in the onboard computer on the basis of data transmitted by the active inertial reference system, SRI2. As the report notes, SRI2 was supposed to contain valid flight data, but instead it contained a diagnostic bit pattern that was interpreted erroneously as flight data. The erroneous data had been declared a failure, and the SRI2 had been shut off. Normally, the on-board computer would have switched to the other inertial reference system, SRI1, but that, too, had been shut down for the same reason.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Tests that might have exposed the problems include tests verifying the behavior of the SRI software under the Ariane-5 countdown, flight time sequence, and trajectory conditions, which were not covered in the original tests.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "no test was performed to verify that the SRI would behave correctly when being subjected to the count-down and flight time sequence and the trajectory of Ariane-5",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Additionally, a risk management plan including risk identification, assumption analysis, and risk avoidance or mitigation plans might have helped prevent the failure by identifying the differences in requirements between Ariane-4 and Ariane-5 software.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The Ariane-5 destruction might have been prevented had the project managers developed a risk management plan, reviewed it, and developed risk avoidance or mitigation plans for each identified risk. The first stage of risk assessment is risk identification. The possible problem with reuse of the Ariane-4 software might have been identified by a decomposition of the functions; someone might have recognized early on that the requirements for Ariane-5 were different from Ariane-4. Or an assumption analysis might have revealed that the assumptions for the SRI in Ariane-4 were different from those for Ariane-5.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

