    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Formal documentation, such as manuals, may be underutilized by users who prefer more interactive or visual training aids like icons, online help, demonstrations, and classes.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In fact, one study showed that only 10% to 15% of the users in an intensive training program read the manual at all. In this and many other cases, users may prefer well-defined icons, online help, demonstrations, and classes to learn how the system works.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Training for users focuses on major system functions relevant to their tasks, without requiring knowledge of internal system operations, which is more relevant for operators.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "User training introduces the primary functions so that users understand what the functions are and how to perform them. Users need not be aware of the system's internal operation. Because these are support functions rather than primary ones, only the operator is concerned with them.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Training and documentation resources can sometimes interfere with software usage when users do not engage with manuals or formal documentation, as studies show only 10% to 15% of users read manuals even after intensive training.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "one study showed that only 10% to 15% of the users in an intensive training program read the manual at all (Scharer 1983). Six months later, no one else had read the user manual, and replacement pages with revised information had not been filed in the manual.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "This lack of engagement suggests that traditional documentation may not be effective for many users, and training aids that rely heavily on manuals can hinder rather than help.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "users may prefer well-defined icons, online help, demonstrations, and classes to learn how the system works.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "To improve training and documentation aids, systems should incorporate more interactive and accessible methods such as icons, online help, demonstrations, and classes that provide feedback and encourage learning through multiple senses.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A system can be designed so that its interface with the user makes system functions clear and easy to understand. Most computer-based systems follow the example of Apple and Xerox in using icons to depict a user's choice of system functions.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Demonstrations and classes usually involve multiple forms of reinforcing what students are learning. Hearing, reading, and seeing how a function works help you to remember functions and techniques more easily.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Additionally, designating expert users as role models and floating instructors can help users feel more comfortable and supported, improving the overall training experience.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Expert users can also be floating instructors after the formal training period is over. They act as consultants, answering questions and making themselves available to others when problems arise.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Finally, training and documentation should be integrated into the system design from the beginning and maintained as the system evolves to ensure they remain relevant and useful.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "training and documentation cannot be an afterthought; they must be designed as the rest of the system is designed, and maintained as the system grows and changes.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The Y2K problem is an example of a maintenance problem caused by a narrow design decision, where many developers represented the year as only two characters, which led to issues when the year rolled over from 99 to 00.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The 'year 2000 problem,' where many developers represented the year as only two characters, is a good example of how simple but narrow design decisions can have a major effect on maintenance.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The maintenance problems listed in section 11.3 include technical problems such as flawed or inflexible design, inadequate design specifications, low-quality programs and documentation, and hardware issues; staff problems such as management priorities overriding technical needs and low morale among maintenance teams.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Technical problems also affect maintenance productivity. Sometimes, they are a legacy of what developers and maintainers have done before.At other times, they result from particular paradigms or processes that have been adopted for the implementation. Artifacts and Paradigms. If the design's logic is not obvious, the team may not easily determine whether the design can handle proposed changes.A flawed or inflexible design can require extra time for understanding, changing, and testing. ... In general, inadequate design specifications and low-quality programs and documentation account for almost 10% of maintenance effort.A similar amount of effort is dedicated to hardware requirements: getting adequate storage and processing time. ... Management Priorities. The maintenance team weighs the desires of the customer's management against the system's needs. Management priorities often override technical ones;managers sometimes view maintaining and enhancing as more important than building new applications. ... Morale. The  Lientz  and  Swanson  studies  (1981)  indicate  that  11.9%  of  the problems during maintenance result from low morale and productivity.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Popular articles discussing the Y2K problem typically focus on the technical design flaw aspect, such as the two-digit year representation, which aligns with the technical problems described in section 11.3.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The 'year 2000 problem,' where many developers represented the year as only two characters, is a good example of how simple but narrow design decisions can have a major effect on maintenance.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "However, issues such as management priorities that lead to rushed, poorly tested changes, and low morale among maintenance staff, which also contribute to maintenance problems, may not be prominently discussed in popular articles about the Y2K problem.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Management priorities often override technical ones;managers sometimes view maintaining and enhancing as more important than building new applications. ... the rush to get a product to market may encourage us, as either developers or maintainers, to implement a quick, inelegant, poorly tested change, rather than take the time to follow good software engineering practice. ... The Lientz and Swanson studies (1981) indicate that 11.9% of the problems during maintenance result from low morale and productivity.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

