[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Empirical studies in software engineering that involve human subjects differ significantly from those that do not, primarily because they must account for human factors such as behavior, experience, and interaction with the technology. For example, a study assessing a new development technique must consider how practitioners actually use the technique in real environments, which introduces variability and uncontrollable factors. This contrasts with studies of algorithms or tools that can be tested in controlled laboratory settings without human involvement, focusing solely on measurable performance metrics like speed or accuracy.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Researchers often perform investigative studies to support decisions about technology. ... techniques such as case studies, field studies, and replicated controlled experiments were considered to be important to the decision-making process in choosing a new technology. ... researchers prefer to perform studies involving reproducible validation methods that can be used in isolation in the laboratory, such as theoretical proof, static analysis, and simulation. They discounted methods that required interacting directly with practitioners.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A recent empirical software study using human subjects might involve case studies or field studies where software practitioners apply a new development technique in their work environment. Such studies must consider effects like the Hawthorne effect, where participants' awareness of being studied can influence their behavior, potentially skewing results. For instance, in testing safety-critical systems, the quality improvement observed might be due to participants knowing they were part of an experiment rather than the technique itself. This highlights the complexity and challenges of empirical studies involving humans, including controlling for biases and ensuring the validity of conclusions.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "- The subjects knew they were participating in an experiment, so the Hawthorne effect may have influenced the results. That is, the fact that the participants knew their products were being evaluated may have caused the increase in quality, not the cleanroom technique itself.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Two different approaches to process improvement discussed in the literature are the use of inspection techniques and the reuse of project knowledge through technology books.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Suppose our organization is interested in modifying the way it performs code inspections. We decide to perform a case study to assess the effects of using a new inspection technique.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The Schlumberger researchers developed technology called project books and technology books, accessible by other developers on other projects, that share experiences, tools, designs, data, ideas, and anything that might be useful to someone else at the company.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The inspection technique approach has been applied in organizations by selecting similar projects (sister projects) to compare the current inspection method with a new one, allowing control over variables and attributing differences in results to the inspection technique used.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "To perform such a study, we select two projects, called sister projects, each of which is typical of the organization and has similar values for the independent variables that we have planned to measure. Then, we perform inspections the current way on the first project and the new way on the second project. By selecting projects that are as similar as possible, we are controlling as much as we can. This situation allows us to attribute any differences in result to the difference in inspection technique.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "When sister projects are not available, the inspection technique approach can be compared against a general baseline derived from organizational data across various projects, which may include descriptive measures such as product size, effort expended, and number of faults discovered.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "However, if we are unable to find two projects similar enough to be sister projects, we can compare our new inspection technique with a general baseline. Here, our company or organization gathers data from its various projects, regardless of how different one project is from another. ... Our case study involves completing a project using the new inspection technique and then comparing the results with the baseline.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The reuse of project knowledge approach, as developed by Schlumberger researchers, involves creating project books and technology books that store and share lessons learned, tools, designs, data, and ideas across projects and developers, facilitating organizational learning and continuous improvement.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The Schlumberger researchers developed technology called project books and technology books, accessible by other developers on other projects, that share experiences, tools, designs, data, ideas, and anything that might be useful to someone else at the company. By using technology such as theirs, we can learn from each other and improve with each project, rather than continue to make the same mistakes and wonder why.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Both approaches have been shown to work in their contexts: the inspection technique approach allows controlled comparison and measurable effects on product quality, while the knowledge reuse approach supports organizational learning and process improvement through shared experiences.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "By selecting projects that are as similar as possible, we are controlling as much as we can. This situation allows us to attribute any differences in result to the difference in inspection technique.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "By using technology such as theirs, we can learn from each other and improve with each project, rather than continue to make the same mistakes and wonder why.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Support required from the organization for the inspection technique approach includes the ability to select comparable projects or maintain a comprehensive project database for baseline comparison, as well as commitment to perform and measure inspections systematically.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Suppose our organization is interested in modifying the way it performs code inspections. We decide to perform a case study to assess the effects of using a new inspection technique. To perform such a study, we select two projects, called sister projects, each of which is typical of the organization and has similar values for the independent variables that we have planned to measure.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In addition to the variable information mentioned before, the data can include descriptive measures, such as product size, effort expended, number of faults discovered, and so on. Then, we can calculate measures of central tendency and dispersion on the data in the database, so we have some idea of the 'average' situation that is typical in our company.",
