[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The recognition-primed decision model describes how individuals make decisions by drawing on a repository of past examples in their heads and comparing the current situation to these past cases to find a close enough match for decision-making.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Klein has suggested a 'recognition-primed decision model,' as shown in Figure 14.6, to describe how we really make decisions. He points out that we tend to keep a repository of examples in our heads, and we draw on these situations when we are confronted with a choice. We mentally refer to a past situation and compare the current one to see if it is similar.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Applying this model directly to an organization by creating an organizational 'experience base' that describes the past work of all employees and can be searched for answers to new problems is an ongoing effort.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "However, there are complications that must be overcome before such systems could be effective.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "Some complications include",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "The decision's context can bias choices, as demonstrated by Hershey, Kunreuther, and Schoemaker (1982), indicating that how a problem is framed affects decision-making.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Hershey, Kunreuther, and Schoemaker (1982) have demonstrated that the decision's context can bias the choice.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Biases such as 'status quo bias' and the preference for case-specific information over general statistical information can influence estimations and decisions, potentially leading to overly optimistic or inaccurate outcomes.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Other sources of bias can creep into decision-making. For example, people usually overvalue what they already own (called 'status quo bias'). ... Individuals exhibit a marked preference for case-specific, or singular, information, as opposed to general statistical, or distributional, information.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Recall is affected by recency and vividness of experience, which may cause important but less recent risks or factors to be discounted.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Recall is affected by both the recency and vividness of an experience. The further into the past a factor occurred, the greater the tendency of the recaller to discount its significance.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Managers and decision-makers may favor estimates and decisions that can be more easily justified, which could bias the system towards certain approaches like algorithmic models over expert judgment.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "'Legitimation' is likely to be both highly significant and somewhat overlooked in the context of software engineering. It is conceivable that estimators and decision-makers may have a preference for estimates and decisions that can be more easily justified.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The context discusses technology transfer in software engineering, focusing on the adoption of new technologies such as software processes, tools, or techniques.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The Future of Software Engineering > 14.2 Technology Transfer",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The anticipated users of new technologies are categorized into types of adopters: innovators, early adopters, early majority, late majority, and laggards, as described by Rogers (1995) and shown in Figure 14.1.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Rogers (1995), in studying technology transfer in many organizations (not just transfers related to software), notes that there are distinct patterns in the way and speed with which technology is adopted.The first people to adopt a technology are innovators ; they probably comprise only 2.5% of the total likely audience, as shown in Figure 14.1.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Innovators are venturesome and rely on personal contact to convince colleagues to try new technology. Early adopters are driven by perceived business benefits and often wait for evidence of success from others before adopting.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Innovators are also people movers, and they rely on personal contact to convince their colleagues to take a risk and try a new technology. Early adopters usually let someone else test the waters first. But when they read about the success of a technology in a respected publication, they build on someone else's success and introduce the technology to their own organizations.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The arguments made as to the technology's effectiveness depend on the type of adopter: innovators focus on technical superiority, early adopters look for tangible evidence about the whole product, early majority seek company impact, and late majority consider market share benefits.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Relative advantage: To what degree is the new technology better than what is already available? Innovators answer this question in technical terms: is it faster, architecturally superior, or more maintainable? Early adopters look for tangible evidence about the 'whole product.' Early-majority adopters seek information about the impact on the company, while late-majority adopters look at how the technology will increase market share.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "According to Figure 14.2, different audiences require different types of evidence: innovators focus on technology itself, early adopters on the product, and mainstream market members on the company and market.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Figure 14.2 summarizes the types of evidence appealing to different audiences. The lower-left quadrant reflects innovators' interests, where the focus is primarily on the technology itself. Early adopters turn their attention to the broader notion of product, while mainstream market members are more interested in the company and the market.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "img",
                "content": null,
                "img_id": "img0_se_theory_practice.pdf__chunk_5821_5824_1337"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The evidence for technology effectiveness should help determine if the new technology causes improvement and reduces uncertainty in development and maintenance processes, making results more predictable.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The overriding goal of technology adoption is to improve at least one new product, process, or resource in some way.The evidence should help us to determine if the new technology causes improvement. We want to investigate the cause-and-effect relationship between the new technology and one or more variables of interest.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Compelling evidence alone is not enough; the technology must be packaged and supported with tools and materials to facilitate adoption, making it 'ready for prime time' for broader diffusion.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "However, compelling evidence is not enough to ensure technology adoption.The marketing world tells us how to package and support the technology to make it 'friendlier' and easier to understand and use. For example, tools and supporting written material go a long way in assisting a user to adopt a new technique or process.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
