[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "To calculate the new object points for each system using the COCOMO 2.0 stage 1 model, we use the complexity weights from Table 3.11: simple screens = 1, medium screens = 2, difficult screens = 3; simple reports = 2, medium reports = 5, difficult reports = 8.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The number to be used for simple, medium, or difficult application points is a complexity weight found in Table 3.11. The weights reflect the relative effort required to implement a report or screen of that complexity level.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "|    | ElementType   | Simple   | Medium   |   Difficult |\n|---:|:--------------|:---------|:---------|------------:|\n|  0 | Screen        | 1        | 2        |           3 |\n|  1 | Report        | 2        | 5        |           8 |",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "For System A, the new object points are calculated as follows: 3 medium screens × 2 points = 6 points, 1 difficult screen × 3 points = 3 points, 2 medium reports × 5 points = 10 points, 1 difficult report × 8 points = 8 points. Total = 6 + 3 + 10 + 8 = 27 new object points.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The number to be used for simple, medium, or difficult application points is a complexity weight found in Table 3.11.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "For System B, the new object points are: 2 medium screens × 2 points = 4 points, 2 difficult screens × 3 points = 6 points, 3 medium reports × 5 points = 15 points. Total = 4 + 6 + 15 = 25 new object points.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The number to be used for simple, medium, or difficult application points is a complexity weight found in Table 3.11.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "Therefore, System A has more new object points than System B.",
        "citations": []
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Kristie's work style is best described as a rational introvert.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The rational introverts also avoid emotional decisions, but they are willing to take time to consider all possible courses of action. Rational introverts are information gatherers; they do not feel comfortable making a decision unless they are convinced that all the facts are at hand.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Kristie seeks out evidence to support her decisions. While carefully considering the objective aspects of the change are important to her, she is also concerned about the opinions of the people who work for her. The members of Kristie's team consider her to be a good listener and often consult her when they have problems.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "This matches the rational introvert profile because she gathers information and considers objective facts before making decisions, and she listens to others rather than just telling them her thoughts.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Rational introverts are information gatherers; they do not feel comfortable making a decision unless they are convinced that all the facts are at hand.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "When communicating ideas, some people tell others their thoughts, and some people ask for suggestions from others before forming an opinion. Jung (1959) calls the former extroverts and the latter introverts.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Shane's work style is best described as a rational extrovert.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Kai, a rational extrovert, judges her colleagues by the results they produce. When making a decision, her top priority is efficiency. Thus, she wants to know only the bottom line. She examines her options and their probable effects, but she does not need to see documents or hear explanations supporting each option. If her time is wasted or her efficiency is hampered in some way, she asserts her authority to regain control of the situation.Thus, Kai is good at making sound decisions quickly.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Jessica's work style could best be described as an intuitive extrovert.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "intuitive extroverts base many decisions on emotional reactions, tending to want to tell others about them rather than ask for input. They use their intuition to be creative, and they often suggest unusual approaches to solving a problem.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "David, an intuitive extrovert... he will trust his intuition about a problem, basing his decision on professional judgment rather than a slow, careful analysis of the information at hand. Since he is assertive, David tends to tell the others on his project about his new ideas. He is creative, and he enjoys when others recognize his ideas.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Matthew's work style can be described as rational introvert.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The rational introverts also avoid emotional decisions, but they are willing to take time to consider all possible courses of action. Rational introverts are information gatherers; they do not feel comfortable making a decision unless they are convinced that all the facts are at hand.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Marcel, a rational introvert, is very different from his colleague Kai. He judges his peers by how busy they are, and he has little tolerance for those who appear not to be working hard all the time. He is a good worker, admired for the energy he devotes to his work. His reputation as a good worker is very important to him, and he prides himself on being accurate and thorough. He does not like to make decisions without complete information.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    }
]

