                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Mills (1972) developed a technique known as fault seeding or error seeding to estimate the number of faults in a program. The basic premise is that one member of the test team intentionally inserts (or 'seeds') a known number of faults in a program. Then, the other team members locate as many faults as possible.The number of undiscovered seeded faults acts as an indicator of the number of total faults (including indigenous, nonseeded ones) remaining in the program.That is, the ratio of seeded faults detected to total seeded faults should be the same as the ratio of nonseeded faults detected to total nonseeded faults"
