[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "To calculate the new object points for the loan search and selection subsystem using the COCOMO 2.0 stage 1 model, we use the formula: New Object Points = (Number of screens × screen weight) + (Number of reports × report weight).",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Suppose the COCOMO 2.0 estimation process has been chosen to estimate size and effort for part of the project.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The weights for screens and reports based on difficulty are: Easy = 1, Medium = 2, Difficult = 3.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Calculating the weighted sum for screens: 2 difficult × 3 + 5 medium × 2 + 3 easy × 1 = 6 + 10 + 3 = 19.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Calculating the weighted sum for reports: 10 difficult × 3 + 6 medium × 2 + 4 easy × 1 = 30 + 12 + 4 = 46.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Total new object points = 19 (screens) + 46 (reports) = 65.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Since there are no 3GL components or reuse, the new object points remain 65.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "None of the provided options (a. 210, b. 137, c. 109, d. 30) match the calculated 65 new object points.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "Therefore, the correct answer is e. None of the above.",
        "citations": []
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The MMRE (Mean Magnitude of Relative Error) is calculated as the average of the absolute values of the relative errors between the estimates and the actual values for each project.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Moreover, Kitchenham, MacDonell, Pickard, and Shepperd (2000) point out that the MMRE and PRED statistics are not direct measures of estimation accuracy. They suggest that you use the simple ratio of estimate to actual: estimate/actual. This measure has a distribution that directly reflects estimation accuracy.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Using the table of estimates and actuals for projects A to F, the relative errors are calculated as follows: |Estimate - Actual| / Actual.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "Relative errors for each project are:",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Project A: |5000 - 10000| / 10000 = 0.5",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Project B: |25000 - 20000| / 20000 = 0.25",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Project C: |50000 - 80000| / 80000 = 0.375",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Project D: |70000 - 110000| / 110000 = 0.3636",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Project E: |40000 - 45000| / 45000 = 0.1111",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Project F: |45000 - 50000| / 50000 = 0.1",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The MMRE is the mean of these relative errors: (0.5 + 0.25 + 0.375 + 0.3636 + 0.1111 + 0.1) / 6 = 0.2833, which rounds to 0.28.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Therefore, the MMRE for the estimation technique is 0.28.",
        "citations": []
    }
]

